00:32:01.265 --> 00:32:02.220
Great.

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:05.560
So how are users actually
discovering apps in Play,

00:32:05.560 --> 00:32:07.814
and what matters to those
discovery mechanisms?

00:32:10.600 --> 00:32:12.570
So let's start with
how users are actually

00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:14.240
finding apps today.

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:17.060
The top discovery
channels on Play

00:32:17.060 --> 00:32:22.370
are number one, Play Search,
two, Recommendations, three,

00:32:22.370 --> 00:32:23.113
Top Charts.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:28.900
So starting with Search.

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:33.910
About half of searches are
specifically for an app title.

00:32:33.910 --> 00:32:37.290
This is where it's especially
important when naming your app

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:42.280
to be unique, keep it short, and
make sure that it is not easily

00:32:42.280 --> 00:32:45.350
confused with a
similarly named app.

00:32:45.350 --> 00:32:47.640
A well-named app
also has the benefit

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.540
of appearing within
Google Play Search

00:32:49.540 --> 00:32:52.770
Suggest, which makes it
even easier for users

00:32:52.770 --> 00:32:54.440
to find your app.

00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:56.250
By using Google
Play Search Suggest,

00:32:56.250 --> 00:33:01.780
they don't even need to type in
the full name to find the app.

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:05.146
Half of searches are also
by category or keyword.

00:33:05.146 --> 00:33:07.020
This is where it's
important to make sure you

00:33:07.020 --> 00:33:10.180
select the right app category.

00:33:10.180 --> 00:33:13.160
Also, when you're writing
the description of your app,

00:33:13.160 --> 00:33:16.340
it's great and important to
be thorough and complete,

00:33:16.340 --> 00:33:19.125
making sure to include key
functionality and features.

00:33:21.989 --> 00:33:23.530
You may have noticed
there's actually

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:27.930
a third way that an app can
appear within given search

00:33:27.930 --> 00:33:30.200
results, and this is ads.

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:33.230
Play Search ads are already
part of AdWords' app

00:33:33.230 --> 00:33:36.260
install campaigns and provide
an additional placement

00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:37.390
within Play Search.

00:33:41.480 --> 00:33:43.240
So Recommendations.

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:45.440
Whether on the Home page
or right after a user

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:49.360
installs an app, Google Play
recommends apps personalized

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:50.447
for each user.

00:33:50.447 --> 00:33:52.030
Although there are
a lot of components

00:33:52.030 --> 00:33:53.510
that go into those
smarts, I just

00:33:53.510 --> 00:33:55.550
want to highlight a
few for you today.

00:33:55.550 --> 00:34:00.630
These include metadata, app
quality, user Store activity,

00:34:00.630 --> 00:34:01.528
and web knowledge.

00:34:04.797 --> 00:34:06.630
LARISSA FONTAINE: So
charts are a common way

00:34:06.630 --> 00:34:10.739
for both new and returning users
to gain a quick understanding

00:34:10.739 --> 00:34:12.690
of which apps are
popular in the Store

00:34:12.690 --> 00:34:15.291
and which apps are on their
way to becoming popular.

00:34:15.291 --> 00:34:16.790
So we're going to
share some insight

00:34:16.790 --> 00:34:18.580
into how these charts
are put together,

00:34:18.580 --> 00:34:20.582
with specific details
on key components.

00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:26.340
Top Free and Top Paid
charts are primarily

00:34:26.340 --> 00:34:29.510
determined by installs
within the last seven days.

00:34:29.510 --> 00:34:31.320
We've kept this
timeline fairly short,

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:34.199
because we want the charts to
stay fresh and interesting week

00:34:34.199 --> 00:34:34.760
over week.

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:40.159
Top New Free and
Top New Paid also

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:43.370
look back at installs over
the previous seven days,

00:34:43.370 --> 00:34:45.460
but they're biased
towards new apps, those

00:34:45.460 --> 00:34:49.110
that have launched on the
Store in the previous 30 days.

00:34:49.110 --> 00:34:51.630
This is important to make sure
the charts aren't dominated

00:34:51.630 --> 00:34:54.540
by established titles.

00:34:54.540 --> 00:34:57.451
We want to help users find new
and interesting apps wherever

00:34:57.451 --> 00:34:58.242
they look for them.

00:35:00.940 --> 00:35:03.090
Trending, on the
other hand, identifies

00:35:03.090 --> 00:35:05.250
fast risers that
have the potential

00:35:05.250 --> 00:35:07.290
to make it onto the top charts.

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:09.300
Typically, this means
that their installs have

00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:12.480
seen accelerated growth
over the previous 30 days,

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:14.310
but their absolute
installs might not

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:16.534
be as large as those on
the other top charts.

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:24.710
And finally, Top Grossing uses
the same seven-day trailing

00:35:24.710 --> 00:35:28.210
approach but is instead
determined by spend.

00:35:28.210 --> 00:35:30.320
And of course, we're always
tuning our algorithms

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:32.460
to produce the best
user experience,

00:35:32.460 --> 00:35:34.260
so these are subject to change.

00:35:34.260 --> 00:35:36.240
But hopefully, you
have a better sense

00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:38.220
of what drives placement
in the top charts

00:35:38.220 --> 00:35:39.822
and how we look
at user preference

00:35:39.822 --> 00:35:41.280
to determine which
apps to surface.

00:35:44.380 --> 00:35:45.590
Featuring.

00:35:45.590 --> 00:35:47.450
Everybody loves featuring.

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:50.240
So we define featuring to
mean the collections that

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:53.310
appear across the store,
either manually curated

00:35:53.310 --> 00:35:55.620
or algorithmically generated.

00:35:55.620 --> 00:35:58.360
Quality is the key
driver for inclusion,

00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:00.970
and that's why we spent the
first half of this talk focused

00:36:00.970 --> 00:36:04.660
on tools and strategies to
help drive important quality

00:36:04.660 --> 00:36:07.200
signals.

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:08.850
In addition to
quality, we also want

00:36:08.850 --> 00:36:11.480
to surface trending apps
to keep the Store fresh,

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:12.980
and we definitely
want users to find

00:36:12.980 --> 00:36:15.480
apps that are using the
latest Android features,

00:36:15.480 --> 00:36:18.112
things that truly make their
experience and their phone

00:36:18.112 --> 00:36:18.612
special.

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:23.940
If you meet the
necessary quality bar,

00:36:23.940 --> 00:36:25.750
your app is eligible
for appearing

00:36:25.750 --> 00:36:28.520
in certain collections where
it makes contextual sense,

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:31.104
fits a category or
topic, or where users

00:36:31.104 --> 00:36:32.270
have installed similar apps.

00:36:34.790 --> 00:36:37.130
With an even higher
expectation of quality,

00:36:37.130 --> 00:36:40.490
we have collections showcasing
new and updated apps,

00:36:40.490 --> 00:36:43.060
so users know they're getting
great experiences that

00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:45.210
are hot off the presses.

00:36:45.210 --> 00:36:47.660
For seasonal collections
and special promotions,

00:36:47.660 --> 00:36:49.820
our BD and merchandising
teams work together

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:51.912
to identify which
apps to include.

00:36:51.912 --> 00:36:53.620
And we also use a
healthy dose of machine

00:36:53.620 --> 00:36:58.446
learning to scale our efforts
across categories and markets.

00:36:58.446 --> 00:37:00.070
It's important to
note that within each

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:03.190
of these collections, the
Recommendations engine helps

00:37:03.190 --> 00:37:06.320
determine which
users see which apps.

00:37:06.320 --> 00:37:08.800
The most important thing is
not that millions of users

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:12.610
see your app, it's that millions
of the right users see your app

00:37:12.610 --> 00:37:14.940
and go on to install it.

